 d-inline-block" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/war/images-videos=
">See all videos for this article</a></figcaption></figure></div></div><p c=
lass=3D"topic-paragraph">Theories centring upon <a href=3D"https://www.brit=
annica.com/topic/human-being" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-pr=
eview=3D"true">man=E2=80=99s</a> innate drives are developed by ethologists=
, who draw <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-ter=
m=3D"analogies" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/analogie=
s" data-type=3D"MW">analogies</a> from animal behaviour, and also by psycho=
logists and psychoanalysts.</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class=3D"marker MOD2 mod-=
inline"></span> <div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-=
level=3D"3" id=3D"ref53513" data-has-spy=3D"true"><h2 class=3D"h3"><span id=
=3D"ref511697"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/etholog=
y" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Ethology</a></h2> <!-=
-[PREMOD3]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD3 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"t=
opic-paragraph">Ethologists start with the persuasive argument that study o=
f <span id=3D"ref511698"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/scien=
ce/animal-behavior" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">anim=
al</a> warfare may contribute toward an understanding of war as employed by=
 man. The behaviour of monkeys and apes in captivity and the behaviour of y=
oung children, for example, show basic similarities. In both cases it is po=
ssible to observe that <span id=3D"ref511699"></span><a href=3D"https://www=
.britannica.com/science/aggressive-behaviour" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-=
show-preview=3D"true">aggressive behaviour</a> usually arises from several =
drives: rivalry for possession, the intrusion of a stranger, or frustration=
 of an activity. The major conflict situations leading to aggression among =
animals, especially those concerning access of males to females and control=
 of a territory for feeding and breeding, are usually associated with patte=
rns of dominance.</p><!--[MOD3]--><span class=3D"marker MOD3 mod-inline"></=
span> <!--[PREMOD4]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD4 mod-inline"></span><p c=
lass=3D"topic-paragraph">The analogies of animal to <span id=3D"ref511700">=
</span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/human-behavior" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">human behaviour</a> drawn by man=
y ethologists, however, are severely questioned by their more restrained co=
lleagues as well as by many social scientists. The term =E2=80=9Caggression=
,=E2=80=9D for example, is imprecisely and inconsistently used, often refer=
ring merely to the largely symbolic behaviour of animals involving such sig=
nals as grimaces.</p><!--[MOD4]--><span class=3D"marker MOD4 mod-inline"></=
span> <!--[PREMOD5]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD5 mod-inline"></span><p c=
lass=3D"topic-paragraph">Observed animal behaviour can be regarded as a pos=
sible important source of inspiration for <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md=
-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"hypotheses" href=3D"https://www.merriam=
-webster.com/dictionary/hypotheses" data-type=3D"MW">hypotheses</a>, but th=
ese must then be checked through the study of actual human behaviour. As th=
is has not yet been adequately done, the hypotheses advanced have little fo=
undation and are merely interesting ideas to be investigated. Further, huma=
n behaviour is not fixed to the extent that animal behaviour is, partly bec=
ause man rapidly evolves different patterns of behaviour in response to env=
ironmental factors, such as geography, climate, and contact with other soci=
al groups. The variety of these behaviour patterns is such that they can be=
 used on both sides of an argument concerning, for example, whether or not =
men have an innate tendency to be aggressive.</p><!--[MOD5]--><span class=
=3D"marker MOD5 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD6]--><span class=3D"marker P=
REMOD6 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Two particularly int=
eresting subjects studied by ethologists are the effects of <span id=3D"ref=
511701"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/overcrowding" =
class=3D"md-crosslink ">overcrowding</a> on animals and animal behaviour re=
garding territory. The study of overcrowding is incomplete, and the finding=
s that normal behaviour patterns tend to break down in such conditions and =
that aggressive behaviour often becomes prominent are subject to the qualif=
ication that animal and human reactions to overcrowding may be different. E=
thologists have also advanced plausible hypotheses concerning biological me=
ans of <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/population-biology-and=
-anthropology" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">=
population</a> control through reduced fertility that occurs when animal po=
pulations increase beyond the capacity of their <a class=3D"md-dictionary-l=
ink md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"environment" href=3D"https://www.=
merriam-webster.com/dictionary/environment" data-type=3D"MW">environment</a=
>. Whether such <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/biological-co=
ntrol" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">biologic=
al control</a> mechanisms operate in human society, however, requires furth=
er investigation.</p><!--[MOD6]--><span class=3D"marker MOD6 mod-inline"></=
span> <!--[PREMOD7]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD7 mod-inline"></span><p c=
lass=3D"topic-paragraph">Findings concerning the =E2=80=9C<span id=3D"ref51=
1702"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/territorial-beha=
viour" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">territorial imper=
ative</a>=E2=80=9D in animals=E2=80=94that is, the demarcation and defense =
against intrusion of a fixed area for feeding and breeding=E2=80=94are even=
 more subject to qualification when an <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-di=
ctionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"analogy" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webst=
er.com/dictionary/analogy" data-type=3D"MW">analogy</a> is drawn from them =
to human behaviour. The analogy between an animal territory and a territori=
al state is obviously extremely <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionar=
y-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"tenuous" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/=
dictionary/tenuous" data-type=3D"MW">tenuous</a>. In nature the territories=
 of members of a species differ in extent but usually seem to be provided w=
ith adequate resources, and use of force in their defense is rarely necessa=
ry, as the customary menacing signals generally lead to the withdrawal of p=
otential rivals. This scarcely compares with the sometimes catastrophic def=
ense of the territory of a national state.</p><!--[MOD7]--><span class=3D"m=
