-blue">(more)</span></button></span></div></figcaption></figure></div></div=
><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">One school of theorists has postulated that t=
he major causes of war can be found in man=E2=80=99s psychological nature. =
Such psychological approaches range from very <a href=3D"https://www.britan=
nica.com/topic/general" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">general</a>, often merely intuitive assertions regarding <a href=
=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/human-nature" class=3D"md-crosslink au=
toxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">human nature</a> to complex analyses ut=
ilizing the concepts and techniques of modern psychology. The former catego=
ry includes a wide range of <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt=
-off mw" data-term=3D"ethical" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dict=
ionary/ethical" data-type=3D"MW">ethical</a> and philosophical teaching and=
 insights, including the works of such figures as <a href=3D"https://www.br=
itannica.com/biography/Saint-Augustine" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-p=
review=3D"true">St. Augustine</a> and the 17th-century Dutch philosopher <a=
 href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Benedict-de-Spinoza" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Benedict de Spinoza</a>.</p><!--=
[MOD8]--><span class=3D"marker MOD8 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD9]--><sp=
an class=3D"marker PREMOD9 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">=
Modern writers utilizing psychological approaches emphasize the significanc=
e of psychological maladjustments or complexes and of false, <a class=3D"md=
-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"stereotyped" href=3D=
"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/stereotyped" data-type=3D"MW">s=
tereotyped</a> images held by decision makers of other countries and their =
leaders. Some psychologists posit an innate aggressiveness in man. Others c=
oncentrate upon <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/public-opinion"=
 class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">public opinion=
</a> and its influence, particularly in times of tension. Others stress the=
 importance of decision makers and the need for their careful selection and=
 training. Most believe that an improved social <span id=3D"ref511704"></sp=
an><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/adjustment-psychology" cla=
ss=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">adjustment</a> of individua=
ls would decrease frustration, insecurity, and fear and would reduce the li=
kelihood of war. All of them believe in the importance of research and <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/education" class=3D"md-crosslink au=
toxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">education</a>. Still, the limitations o=
f such approaches derive from their very generality. Also, whether the psyc=
hological <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=
=3D"premises" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/premises" =
data-type=3D"MW">premises</a> are optimistic or pessimistic about the natur=
e of man, one cannot ignore the impact upon human behaviour of social and p=
olitical institutions that give man the opportunities to exercise his good =
or evil <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=
=3D"propensities" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/propen=
sities" data-type=3D"MW">propensities</a> and to impose restraints upon him=
.</p><!--[MOD9]--><span class=3D"marker MOD9 mod-inline"></span></section><=
